width=3D15 height=3D11></A></DIV>A cryptographic hash function =
(specifically, <A=20
title=3DSHA-1 href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SHA-1">SHA-1</A>) at =
work. Note=20
that even small changes in the source input (here in the word "over")=20
drastically change the resulting output, by the so-called <A=20
title=3D"Avalanche effect"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Avalanche_effect">avalanche=20
effect</A>.</DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>A <B>cryptographic hash function</B> is a <A title=3D"Hash function"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hash_function">hash function</A>; =
that is, an=20
<A title=3DAlgorithm =
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithm">algorithm</A>=20
that takes an arbitrary block of <A title=3DData=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data">data</A> and returns a =
fixed-size <A=20
title=3DBit href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bit">bit</A> string, =
the=20
(<B>cryptographic</B>) <B>hash value</B>, such that any (accidental or=20
intentional) change to the data will (with very high probability) change =
the=20
hash value. The data to be encoded are often called the "message," and =
the hash=20
value is sometimes called the <B>message digest</B> or simply =
<B>digest.</B></P>
<P>The ideal cryptographic hash function has four main properties:</P>
<UL>
  <LI>it is easy to compute the hash value for any given message</LI>
  <LI>it is <A title=3D"Computational complexity theory"=20
  =
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computational_complexity_theory#Intr=
actability">infeasible</A>=20
  to generate a message that has a given hash</LI>
  <LI>it is infeasible to modify a message without changing the =
hash</LI>
  <LI>it is infeasible to find two different messages with the same =
hash</LI></UL>
<P>Cryptographic hash functions have many <A title=3D"Information =
security"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Information_security">information=20
security</A> applications, notably in <A title=3D"Digital signature"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital_signature">digital =
signatures</A>, <A=20
class=3Dmw-redirect title=3D"Message authentication codes"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Message_authentication_codes">messag=
e=20
authentication codes</A> (MACs), and other forms of <A =
title=3DAuthentication=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Authentication">authentication</A>. =
They can=20
also be used as ordinary <A title=3D"Hash function"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hash_function">hash functions</A>, =
to index=20
data in <A title=3D"Hash table"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hash_table">hash tables</A>, for <A =

title=3D"Fingerprint (computing)"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fingerprint_(computing)">fingerprint=
ing</A>,=20
to detect duplicate data or uniquely identify files, and as <A =
title=3DChecksum=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Checksum">checksums</A> to detect =
accidental=20
data corruption. Indeed, in information security contexts, cryptographic =
hash=20
values are sometimes called (<B>digital</B>) <B>fingerprints,</B>=20
<B>checksums,</B> or just <B>hash values,</B> even though all these =
terms stand=20
for functions with rather different properties and purposes.</P>
