<H2><SPAN class=3Deditsection>[<A title=3D"Edit section: Properties"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCryptographic_hash_fu=
nction&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1">edit</A>]</SPAN>=20
<SPAN id=3DProperties class=3Dmw-headline>Properties</SPAN></H2>
<P>Most cryptographic hash functions are designed to take a <A=20
title=3D"String (computer science)"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/String_(computer_science)">string</A=
> of any=20
length as input and produce a fixed-length hash value.</P>
<P>A cryptographic hash function must be able to withstand all known <A=20
title=3DCryptanalysis=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptanalysis#Types_of_cryptanalytic=
_attack">types=20
of cryptanalytic attack</A>. As a minimum, it must have the following=20
properties:</P>
<UL>
  <LI><I>Pre-image resistance</I>=20
  <DL>
    <DD>Given a hash <I>h</I> it should be difficult to find any message =

    <I>m</I> such that <I>h =3D hash(m)</I>. This concept is related to =
that of <A=20
    title=3D"One-way function"=20
    href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One-way_function">one-way =
function</A>.=20
    Functions that lack this property are vulnerable to <A=20
    title=3D"Preimage attack"=20
    href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Preimage_attack">preimage=20
    attacks</A>.</DD></DL></LI>
  <LI><I>Second pre-image resistance</I>=20
  <DL>
    <DD>Given an input <I>m</I><SUB>1</SUB> it should be difficult to =
find=20
    another input <I>m</I><SUB>2</SUB> such that <SPAN=20
    class=3Dnowrap><I>m</I><SUB>1</SUB> =E2=89=A0 =
<I>m</I><SUB>2</SUB></SPAN> and <SPAN=20
    class=3Dnowrap><I>hash</I>(<I>m</I><SUB>1</SUB>) =3D=20
    <I>hash</I>(<I>m</I><SUB>2</SUB>)</SPAN>. This property is sometimes =

    referred to as <I>weak collision resistance,</I> and functions that =
lack=20
    this property are vulnerable to <A title=3D"Preimage attack"=20
    =
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Preimage_attack">second-preimage=20
    attacks</A>.</DD></DL></LI>
  <LI><I><A title=3D"Collision resistance"=20
  href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collision_resistance">Collision=20
  resistance</A></I>=20
  <DL>
    <DD>It should be difficult to find two different messages=20
    <I>m</I><SUB>1</SUB> and <I>m</I><SUB>2</SUB> such that <SPAN=20
    class=3Dnowrap><I>hash</I>(<I>m</I><SUB>1</SUB>) =3D=20
    <I>hash</I>(<I>m</I><SUB>2</SUB>)</SPAN>. Such a pair is called a=20
    cryptographic <A class=3Dmw-redirect title=3D"Hash collision"=20
    href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hash_collision">hash =
collision</A>. This=20
    property is sometimes referred to as <I>strong collision =
resistance.</I> It=20
    requires a hash value at least twice as long as that required for=20
    preimage-resistance; otherwise collisions may be found by a <A=20
    title=3D"Birthday attack"=20
    href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Birthday_attack">birthday=20
  attack</A>.</DD></DL></LI></UL>
<P>These properties imply that a <A title=3D"Adversary (cryptography)"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adversary_(cryptography)">malicious =

adversary</A> cannot replace or modify the input data without changing =
its=20
digest. Thus, if two strings have the same digest, one can be very =
confident=20
that they are identical.</P>
<P>A function meeting these criteria may still have undesirable =
properties.=20
Currently popular cryptographic hash functions are vulnerable to <A=20
title=3D"Length extension attack"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Length_extension_attack"><I>length-e=
xtension</I>=20
attacks</A>: given <SPAN class=3Dnowrap><I>hash</I>(<I>m</I>)</SPAN> and =
<SPAN=20
class=3Dnowrap><I>len</I>(<I>m</I>)</SPAN> but not <I>m</I>, by choosing =
a=20
suitable <I>m</I><SPAN style=3D"PADDING-LEFT: 0.1em">'</SPAN> an =
attacker can=20
calculate <SPAN class=3Dnowrap><I>hash</I>(<I>m</I> || <I>m</I><SPAN=20
style=3D"PADDING-LEFT: 0.1em">'</SPAN>)</SPAN> where || denotes <A=20
title=3DConcatenation=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Concatenation">concatenation</A>.<SU=
P=20
id=3Dcite_ref-1 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCryptographic_hash_fu=
nction&amp;oldid=3D537036494#cite_note-1"><SPAN>[</SPAN>1<SPAN>]</SPAN></=
A></SUP>=20
This property can be used to break naive authentication schemes based on =
hash=20
functions. The <A class=3Dmw-redirect title=3DHMAC=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HMAC">HMAC</A> construction works =
around=20
these problems.</P>
<P>Ideally, one may wish for even stronger conditions. It should be =
impossible=20
for an adversary to find two messages with substantially similar =
digests; or to=20
infer any useful information about the data, given only its digest. =
Therefore, a=20
cryptographic hash function should behave as much as possible like a <A=20
title=3D"Random function"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_function">random =
function</A> while=20
still being deterministic and efficiently computable.</P>
<P>Checksum algorithms, such as <A class=3Dmw-redirect title=3DCRC32=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CRC32">CRC32</A> and other <A=20
title=3D"Cyclic redundancy check"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyclic_redundancy_check">cyclic =
redundancy=20
checks</A>, are designed to meet much weaker requirements, and are =
generally=20
unsuitable as cryptographic hash functions. For example, a CRC was used =
for=20
message integrity in the <A title=3D"Wired Equivalent Privacy"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wired_Equivalent_Privacy">WEP</A> =
encryption=20
standard, but an attack was readily discovered which exploited the =
linearity of=20
the checksum.</P>
<H3><SPAN class=3Deditsection>[<A title=3D"Edit section: Degree of =
difficulty"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCryptographic_hash_fu=
nction&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2">edit</A>]</SPAN>=20
<SPAN id=3DDegree_of_difficulty class=3Dmw-headline>Degree of =
difficulty</SPAN></H3>
<P>In cryptographic practice, =E2=80=9Cdifficult=E2=80=9D generally =
means =E2=80=9Calmost certainly=20
beyond the reach of any adversary who must be prevented from breaking =
the system=20
for as long as the security of the system is deemed important.=E2=80=9D =
The meaning of=20
the term is therefore somewhat dependent on the application, since the =
effort=20
that a malicious agent may put into the task is usually proportional to =
his=20
expected gain. However, since the needed effort usually grows very =
quickly with=20
the digest length, even a thousand-fold advantage in processing power =
can be=20
neutralized by adding a few dozen bits to the latter.</P>
<P>In some <A title=3D"Computational complexity theory"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computational_complexity_theory">the=
oretical=20
analyses</A> =E2=80=9Cdifficult=E2=80=9D has a specific mathematical =
meaning, such as <I>not=20
solvable in <A title=3D"Asymptotic computational complexity"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asymptotic_computational_complexity"=
>asymptotic</A>=20
<A class=3Dmw-redirect title=3D"Polynomial time"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial_time">polynomial =
time</A>.</I>=20
Such interpretations of <I>difficulty</I> are important in the study of =
<A=20
title=3D"Provably secure cryptographic hash function"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Provably_secure_cryptographic_hash_f=
unction">provably=20
secure cryptographic hash functions</A> but do not usually have a strong =

connection to practical security. For example, an <A class=3Dmw-redirect =

title=3D"Exponential time"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponential_time">exponential =
time</A>=20
algorithm can sometimes still be fast enough to make a feasible attack.=20
Conversely, a polynomial time algorithm (e.g., one that requires=20
<I>n</I><SUP>20</SUP> steps for <I>n</I>-digit keys) may be too slow for =
any=20
practical use.</P>
<H2><SPAN class=3Deditsection>[<A title=3D"Edit section: Illustration"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCryptographic_hash_fu=
nction&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3">edit</A>]</SPAN>=20
<SPAN id=3DIllustration class=3Dmw-headline>Illustration</SPAN></H2>
<P>An illustration of the potential use of a cryptographic hash is as =
follows:=20
<A title=3D"Alice and Bob"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alice_and_Bob">Alice</A> poses a =
tough math=20
problem to <A title=3D"Alice and Bob"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alice_and_Bob">Bob</A> and claims =
she has=20
solved it. Bob would like to try it himself, but would yet like to be =
sure that=20
Alice is not bluffing. Therefore, Alice writes down her solution, =
computes its=20
hash and tells Bob the hash value (whilst keeping the solution secret). =
Then,=20
when Bob comes up with the solution himself a few days later, Alice can =
prove=20
that she had the solution earlier by revealing it and having Bob hash it =
and=20
check that it matches the hash value given to him before. (This is an =
example of=20
a simple <A title=3D"Commitment scheme"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commitment_scheme">commitment =
scheme</A>; in=20
actual practice, Alice and Bob will often be computer programs, and the =
secret=20
would be something less easily spoofed than a claimed puzzle =
solution).</P>
<H2><SPAN class=3Deditsection>[<A title=3D"Edit section: Applications"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCryptographic_hash_fu=
nction&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4">edit</A>]</SPAN>=20
<SPAN id=3DApplications class=3Dmw-headline>Applications</SPAN></H2>
<H3><SPAN class=3Deditsection>[<A=20
title=3D"Edit section: Verifying the integrity of files or messages"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCryptographic_hash_fu=
nction&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5">edit</A>]</SPAN>=20
<SPAN id=3DVerifying_the_integrity_of_files_or_messages=20
class=3Dmw-headline>Verifying the integrity of files or =
messages</SPAN></H3>
<P>An important application of secure hashes is verification of <A=20
class=3Dmw-redirect title=3D"Message integrity"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Message_integrity">message =
integrity</A>.=20
Determining whether any changes have been made to a message (or a <A=20
title=3D"Computer file"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_file">file</A>), for =
example, can be=20
accomplished by comparing message digests calculated before, and after,=20
transmission (or any other event).</P>
<P>For this reason, most <A title=3D"Digital signature"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital_signature">digital =
signature</A>=20
algorithms only confirm the authenticity of a hashed digest of the =
message to be=20
"signed." Verifying the authenticity of a hashed digest of the message =
is=20
considered proof that the message itself is authentic.</P>
<H3><SPAN class=3Deditsection>[<A title=3D"Edit section: Password =
verification"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCryptographic_hash_fu=
nction&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6">edit</A>]</SPAN>=20
<SPAN id=3DPassword_verification class=3Dmw-headline>Password=20
verification</SPAN></H3>
<P>A related application is <A title=3DPassword=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Password">password</A> =
verification.=20
Passwords are usually not stored in <A class=3Dmw-redirect =
title=3DCleartext=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cleartext">cleartext</A>, but =
instead in=20
digest form, to improve security. To authenticate a user, the password =
presented=20
by the user is hashed and compared with the stored hash. This also means =
that=20
the original passwords cannot be retrieved if forgotten or lost, and =
they have=20
to be replaced with new ones. The password is often concatenated with a =
random,=20
non-secret <A title=3D"Salt (cryptography)"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salt_(cryptography)">salt</A> value =
that is=20
stored with the password. Because users have different salts, it is not =
feasible=20
to store tables of <A title=3DPrecomputation=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Precomputation">precomputed</A> =
hash values=20
for common passwords. <A title=3D"Key stretching"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Key_stretching">Key stretching</A> =
functions,=20
such as <A title=3DPBKDF2 =
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PBKDF2">PBKDF2</A>,=20
typically use repeated invocations of a cryptographic hash to increase =
the time=20
required to perform <A class=3Dmw-redirect title=3D"Brute force attack"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brute_force_attack">brute force =
attacks</A>=20
on stored password digests.</P>
<H3><SPAN class=3Deditsection>[<A title=3D"Edit section: File or data =
identifier"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCryptographic_hash_fu=
nction&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7">edit</A>]</SPAN>=20
<SPAN id=3DFile_or_data_identifier class=3Dmw-headline>File or data=20
identifier</SPAN></H3>
<P>A message digest can also serve as a means of reliably identifying a =
file;=20
several <A class=3Dmw-redirect title=3D"Source Code Management"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Source_Code_Management">source code =

management</A> systems, including <A title=3D"Git (software)"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Git_(software)">Git</A>, <A =
class=3Dmw-redirect=20
title=3D"Mercurial (software)"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mercurial_(software)">Mercurial</A> =
and <A=20
title=3D"Monotone (software)"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monotone_(software)">Monotone</A>, =
use the <A=20
title=3DSha1sum =
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sha1sum">sha1sum</A> of various=20
types of content (file content, directory trees, ancestry information, =
etc.) to=20
uniquely identify them. Hashes are used to identify files on <A=20
title=3DPeer-to-peer=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peer-to-peer">peer-to-peer</A> <A=20
class=3Dmw-redirect title=3DFilesharing=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Filesharing">filesharing</A> =
networks. For=20
example, in an <A class=3Dmw-redirect title=3D"Ed2k link"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ed2k_link">ed2k link</A>, an <A =
title=3DMD4=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MD4">MD4</A>-variant hash is =
combined with=20
the file size, providing sufficient information for locating file =
sources,=20
downloading the file and verifying its contents. <A title=3D"Magnet URI =
scheme"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnet_URI_scheme">Magnet links</A> =
are=20
another example. Such file hashes are often the top hash of a <A=20
title=3D"Hash list" href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hash_list">hash =
list</A> or=20
a <A title=3D"Hash tree" =
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hash_tree">hash=20
tree</A> which allows for additional benefits.</P>
<P>One of the main applications of a <A title=3D"Hash function"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hash_function">hash function</A> is =
to allow=20
the fast look-up of a data in a <A title=3D"Hash table"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hash_table">hash table</A>. Being =
hash=20
functions of a particular kind, cryptographic hash functions lend =
themselves=20
well to this application too.</P>
<P>However, compared with standard hash functions, cryptographic hash =
functions=20
tend to be much more expensive computationally. For this reason, they =
tend to be=20
used in contexts where it is necessary for users to protect themselves =
against=20
the possibility of forgery (the creation of data with the same digest as =
the=20
expected data) by potentially malicious participants.</P>
<H3><SPAN class=3Deditsection>[<A=20
title=3D"Edit section: Pseudorandom generation and key derivation"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCryptographic_hash_fu=
nction&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8">edit</A>]</SPAN>=20
<SPAN id=3DPseudorandom_generation_and_key_derivation=20
class=3Dmw-headline>Pseudorandom generation and key =
derivation</SPAN></H3>
<P>Hash functions can also be used in the generation of <A =
class=3Dmw-redirect=20
title=3DPseudorandom=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pseudorandom">pseudorandom</A> =
bits, or to <A=20
title=3D"Key derivation function"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Key_derivation_function">derive new =
keys or=20
passwords</A> from a single, secure key or password.</P>
<H2><SPAN class=3Deditsection>[<A=20
title=3D"Edit section: Hash functions based on block ciphers"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCryptographic_hash_fu=
nction&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9">edit</A>]</SPAN>=20
<SPAN id=3DHash_functions_based_on_block_ciphers =
class=3Dmw-headline>Hash functions=20
based on block ciphers</SPAN></H2>
<P>There are several methods to use a <A title=3D"Block cipher"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Block_cipher">block cipher</A> to =
build a=20
cryptographic hash function, specifically a <A=20
title=3D"One-way compression function"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One-way_compression_function">one-wa=
y=20
compression function</A>.</P>
<P>The methods resemble the <A title=3D"Block cipher modes of operation" =

href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Block_cipher_modes_of_operation">blo=
ck cipher=20
modes of operation</A> usually used for encryption. All well-known hash=20
functions, including <A title=3DMD4=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MD4">MD4</A>, <A title=3DMD5=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MD5">MD5</A>, <A title=3DSHA-1=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SHA-1">SHA-1</A> and <A =
title=3DSHA-2=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SHA-2">SHA-2</A> are built from=20
block-cipher-like components designed for the purpose, with feedback to =
ensure=20
that the resulting function is not invertible. <A=20
title=3D"NIST hash function competition"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NIST_hash_function_competition">SHA-=
3</A>=20
finalists included functions with block-cipher-like components (e.g., <A =

class=3Dmw-redirect title=3D"Skein hash function"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skein_hash_function">Skein</A>, =
BLAKE) though=20
the function finally selected, <A class=3Dmw-redirect title=3DKeccak=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keccak">Keccak</A>, was built on a =
<A=20
title=3D"Sponge function"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sponge_function">cryptographic =
sponge</A>=20
instead.</P>
<P>A standard block cipher such as <A title=3D"Advanced Encryption =
Standard"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Advanced_Encryption_Standard">AES</A=
> can be=20
used in place of these custom block ciphers; that might be useful when =
an <A=20
title=3D"Embedded system"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Embedded_system">embedded =
system</A> needs to=20
implement both encryption and hashing with minimal code size or hardware =
area.=20
However, that approach can have costs in efficiency and security. The =
ciphers in=20
hash functions are built for hashing: they use large keys and blocks, =
can=20
efficiently change keys every block, and have been designed and vetted =
for=20
resistance to <A title=3D"Related-key attack"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Related-key_attack">related-key =
attacks</A>.=20
General-purpose ciphers tend to have different design goals. In =
particular, AES=20
has key and block sizes that make it nontrivial to use to generate long =
hash=20
values; AES encryption becomes less efficient when the key changes each =
block;=20
and related-key attacks make it potentially less secure for use in a =
hash=20
function than for encryption.</P>
<H2><SPAN class=3Deditsection>[<A=20
title=3D"Edit section: Merkle=E2=80=93Damg=C3=A5rd construction"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCryptographic_hash_fu=
nction&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10">edit</A>]</SPAN>=20
<SPAN id=3DMerkle.E2.80.93Damg.C3.A5rd_construction=20
class=3Dmw-headline>Merkle=E2=80=93Damg=C3=A5rd construction</SPAN></H2>
<DIV class=3D"rellink relarticle mainarticle">Main article: <A=20
title=3D"Merkle=E2=80=93Damg=C3=A5rd construction"=20
