<P>A hash function must be able to process an arbitrary-length message =
into a=20
fixed-length output. This can be achieved by breaking the input up into =
a series=20
of equal-sized blocks, and operating on them in sequence using a one-way =

compression function. The compression function can either be specially =
designed=20
for hashing or be built from a block cipher. A hash function built with =
the=20
Merkle=E2=80=93Damg=C3=A5rd construction is as resistant to collisions =
as is its compression=20
function; any collision for the full hash function can be traced back to =
a=20
collision in the compression function.</P>
<P>The last block processed should also be unambiguously <A=20
title=3D"Padding (cryptography)"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Padding_(cryptography)">length =
padded</A>;=20
this is crucial to the security of this construction. This construction =
is=20
called the <A title=3D"Merkle=E2=80=93Damg=C3=A5rd construction"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Merkle%E2%80%93Damg%C3%A5rd_construc=
tion">Merkle=E2=80=93Damg=C3=A5rd=20
construction</A>. Most widely used hash functions, including <A =
title=3DSHA-1=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SHA-1">SHA-1</A> and <A title=3DMD5 =

href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MD5">MD5</A>, take this form.</P>
<P>The construction has certain inherent flaws, including =
length-extension and=20
generate-and-paste attacks, and cannot be parallelized. As a result, =
many=20
entrants in the current <A title=3D"NIST hash function competition"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NIST_hash_function_competition">NIST=
 hash=20
function competition</A> are built on different, sometimes novel,=20
constructions.</P>
<H2><SPAN class=3Deditsection>[<A=20
title=3D"Edit section: Use in building other cryptographic primitives"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCryptographic_hash_fu=
nction&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11">edit</A>]</SPAN>=20
<SPAN id=3DUse_in_building_other_cryptographic_primitives =
class=3Dmw-headline>Use in=20
building other cryptographic primitives</SPAN></H2>
<P>Hash functions can be used to build other cryptographic primitives. =
For these=20
other primitives to be cryptographically secure, care must be taken to =
build=20
them correctly.</P>
<P><A title=3D"Message authentication code"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Message_authentication_code">Message=
=20
authentication codes</A> (MACs) (also called keyed hash functions) are =
often=20
built from hash functions. <A class=3Dmw-redirect title=3DHMAC=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HMAC">HMAC</A> is such a MAC.</P>
<P>Just as <A title=3D"Block cipher"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Block_cipher">block ciphers</A> can =
be used=20
to build hash functions, hash functions can be used to build block =
ciphers. <A=20
class=3Dmw-redirect title=3DLuby-Rackoff=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Luby-Rackoff">Luby-Rackoff</A> =
constructions=20
using hash functions can be provably secure if the underlying hash =
function is=20
secure. Also, many hash functions (including <A title=3DSHA-1=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SHA-1">SHA-1</A> and <A =
title=3DSHA-2=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SHA-2">SHA-2</A>) are built by =
using a=20
special-purpose block cipher in a <A title=3D"One-way compression =
function"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One-way_compression_function#Davies.=
E2.80.93Meyer">Davies-Meyer</A>=20
or other construction. That cipher can also be used in a conventional =
mode of=20
operation, without the same security guarantees. See <A title=3DSHACAL=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SHACAL">SHACAL</A>, <A =
class=3Dmw-redirect=20
title=3D"BEAR (cipher)" =
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BEAR_(cipher)">BEAR</A>=20
and <A class=3Dmw-redirect title=3D"LION (cipher)"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LION_(cipher)">LION</A>.</P>
<P><A title=3D"Pseudorandom number generator"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pseudorandom_number_generator">Pseud=
orandom=20
number generators</A> (PRNGs) can be built using hash functions. This is =
done by=20
combining a (secret) random seed with a counter and hashing it.</P>
<P>Some hash functions, such as <A title=3D"Skein (hash function)"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skein_(hash_function)">Skein</A>, =
<A=20
class=3Dmw-redirect title=3DKeccak=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keccak">Keccak</A>, and <A =
title=3DRadioGat=C3=BAn=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RadioGat%C3%BAn">RadioGat=C3=BAn</A>=
 output an=20
arbitrarily long stream and can be used as a <A title=3D"Stream cipher"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stream_cipher">stream cipher</A>, =
and stream=20
ciphers can also be built from fixed-length digest hash functions. Often =
this is=20
done by first building a <A=20
title=3D"Cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generator"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptographically_secure_pseudorando=
m_number_generator">cryptographically=20
secure pseudorandom number generator</A> and then using its stream of =
random=20
bytes as <A title=3DKeystream=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keystream">keystream</A>. <A=20
title=3D"SEAL (cipher)" =
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SEAL_(cipher)">SEAL</A>=20
is a stream cipher that uses <A title=3DSHA-1=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SHA-1">SHA-1</A> to generate =
internal tables,=20
which are then used in a keystream generator more or less unrelated to =
the hash=20
algorithm. SEAL is not guaranteed to be as strong (or weak) as =
SHA-1.</P>
<H2><SPAN class=3Deditsection>[<A=20
title=3D"Edit section: Concatenation of cryptographic hash functions"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCryptographic_hash_fu=
nction&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12">edit</A>]</SPAN>=20
<SPAN id=3DConcatenation_of_cryptographic_hash_functions=20
class=3Dmw-headline>Concatenation of cryptographic hash =
functions</SPAN></H2>
<P>Concatenating outputs from multiple hash functions provides collision =

resistance as good as the strongest of the algorithms included in the=20
concatenated result. For example, older versions of <A=20
title=3D"Transport Layer Security"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transport_Layer_Security">TLS/SSL</A=
> use=20
concatenated <A title=3DMD5 =
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MD5">MD5</A> and <A=20
title=3DSHA-1 href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SHA-1">SHA-1</A> =
sums; that=20
ensures that a method to find collisions in one of the functions doesn't =
allow=20
forging traffic protected with both functions.</P>
<P>For Merkle-Damg=C3=A5rd hash functions, the concatenated function is =
as=20
collision-resistant as its strongest component,<SUP id=3Dcite_ref-2=20
class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCryptographic_hash_fu=
nction&amp;oldid=3D537036494#cite_note-2"><SPAN>[</SPAN>2<SPAN>]</SPAN></=
A></SUP>=20
but not more collision-resistant.<SUP id=3Dcite_ref-3 =
class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCryptographic_hash_fu=
nction&amp;oldid=3D537036494#cite_note-3"><SPAN>[</SPAN>3<SPAN>]</SPAN></=
A></SUP>=20
Joux<SUP id=3Dcite_ref-4 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCryptographic_hash_fu=
nction&amp;oldid=3D537036494#cite_note-4"><SPAN>[</SPAN>4<SPAN>]</SPAN></=
A></SUP>=20
noted that 2-collisions lead to n-collisions: if it is feasible to find =
two=20
messages with the same MD5 hash, it is effectively no more difficult to =
find as=20
many messages as the attacker desires with identical MD5 hashes. Among =
the n=20
messages with the same MD5 hash, there is likely to be a collision in =
SHA-1. The=20
additional work needed to find the SHA-1 collision (beyond the =
exponential=20
birthday search) is <A class=3Dmw-redirect title=3D"Polynomial time"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial_time">polynomial</A>. =
This=20
argument is summarized by <A class=3D"external text"=20
href=3D"http://article.gmane.org/gmane.comp.encryption.general/5154"=20
rel=3Dnofollow>Finney</A>. A more current paper and full proof of the =
security of=20
such a combined construction gives a clearer and more complete =
explanation of=20
the above.<SUP id=3Dcite_ref-5 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCryptographic_hash_fu=
nction&amp;oldid=3D537036494#cite_note-5"><SPAN>[</SPAN>5<SPAN>]</SPAN></=
A></SUP></P>
<H2><SPAN class=3Deditsection>[<A=20
title=3D"Edit section: Cryptographic hash algorithms"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCryptographic_hash_fu=
nction&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13">edit</A>]</SPAN>=20
<SPAN id=3DCryptographic_hash_algorithms =
class=3Dmw-headline>Cryptographic hash=20
algorithms</SPAN></H2>
<P>There is a long list of cryptographic hash functions, although many =
have been=20
found to be vulnerable and should not be used. Even if a hash function =
has never=20
been broken, a successful attack against a weakened variant thereof may=20
undermine the experts' confidence and lead to its abandonment. For =
instance, in=20
August 2004 weaknesses were found in a number of hash functions that =
were=20
popular at the time, including SHA-0, RIPEMD, and MD5. This has called =
into=20
question the long-term security of later algorithms which are derived =
from these=20
hash functions&nbsp;=E2=80=94 in particular, SHA-1 (a strengthened =
version of SHA-0),=20
RIPEMD-128, and RIPEMD-160 (both strengthened versions of RIPEMD). =
Neither SHA-0=20
nor RIPEMD are widely used since they were replaced by their =
strengthened=20
versions.</P>
<P>As of 2009, the two most commonly used cryptographic hash functions =
are <A=20
title=3DMD5 href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MD5">MD5</A> and <A =
title=3DSHA-1=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SHA-1">SHA-1</A>. However, MD5 has =
been=20
broken; an attack against it was used to break <A=20
title=3D"Transport Layer Security"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transport_Layer_Security">SSL</A> =
in=20
2008.<SUP id=3Dcite_ref-6 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCryptographic_hash_fu=
nction&amp;oldid=3D537036494#cite_note-6"><SPAN>[</SPAN>6<SPAN>]</SPAN></=
A></SUP></P>
<P>The <A class=3Dmw-redirect title=3DSHA-0=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SHA-0">SHA-0</A> and <A =
title=3DSHA-1=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SHA-1">SHA-1</A> hash functions =
were=20
developed by the <A class=3Dmw-redirect title=3DNSA=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA">NSA</A>. In February 2005, a =
successful=20
attack on SHA-1 was reported, finding collisions in about 2<SUP>69</SUP> =
hashing=20
operations, rather than the 2<SUP>80</SUP> expected for a 160-bit hash =
function.=20
In August 2005, another successful attack on SHA-1 was reported, finding =

collisions in 2<SUP>63</SUP> operations. Theoretical weaknesses of SHA-1 =
exist=20
as well,<SUP id=3Dcite_ref-7 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCryptographic_hash_fu=
nction&amp;oldid=3D537036494#cite_note-7"><SPAN>[</SPAN>7<SPAN>]</SPAN></=
A></SUP><SUP=20
id=3Dcite_ref-8 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCryptographic_hash_fu=
nction&amp;oldid=3D537036494#cite_note-8"><SPAN>[</SPAN>8<SPAN>]</SPAN></=
A></SUP>=20
suggesting that it may be practical to break within years. New =
applications can=20
avoid these problems by using more advanced members of the SHA family, =
such as=20
<A title=3DSHA-2 href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SHA-2">SHA-2</A>, =
or using=20
techniques such as randomized hashing<SUP id=3Dcite_ref-9 =
class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCryptographic_hash_fu=
nction&amp;oldid=3D537036494#cite_note-9"><SPAN>[</SPAN>9<SPAN>]</SPAN></=
A></SUP><SUP=20
id=3Dcite_ref-10 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCryptographic_hash_fu=
nction&amp;oldid=3D537036494#cite_note-10"><SPAN>[</SPAN>10<SPAN>]</SPAN>=
</A></SUP>=20
that do not require collision resistance.</P>
<P>However, to ensure the long-term robustness of applications that use =
hash=20
functions, there was a <A title=3D"NIST hash function competition"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NIST_hash_function_competition">comp=
etition</A>=20
to design a replacement for SHA-2, which was given the name <A =
title=3DSHA-3=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SHA-3">SHA-3</A> and became a <A=20
title=3D"Federal Information Processing Standard"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Federal_Information_Processing_Stand=
ard">FIPS</A>=20
standard in 2012.<SUP id=3Dcite_ref-11 class=3Dreference><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCryptographic_hash_fu=
nction&amp;oldid=3D537036494#cite_note-11"><SPAN>[</SPAN>11<SPAN>]</SPAN>=
</A></SUP>=20
On October 2, 2012, Keccak was selected as the winner of the <A=20
title=3D"National Institute of Standards and Technology"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Institute_of_Standards_and_=
Technology">NIST</A>=20
hash function competition.</P>
<P>Some of the following algorithms are used often in cryptography; =
consult the=20
article for each specific algorithm for more information on the status =
of each=20
algorithm. Note that this list does not include candidates in the =
current NIST=20
hash function competition. For additional hash functions see the box at =
the=20
bottom of the page.</P>
