nction&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14">edit</A>]</SPAN>=20
<SPAN id=3DNotes class=3Dmw-headline>Notes</SPAN></H3>
<OL class=3Dreferences>
  <LI id=3Dcite_note-12><SPAN class=3Dmw-cite-backlink><B><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCryptographic_hash_fu=
nction&amp;oldid=3D537036494#cite_ref-12">^</A></B></SPAN>=20
  <SPAN class=3Dreference-text>The <I>internal state</I> here means the =
"internal=20
  hash sum" after each compression of a data block. Most hash algorithms =
also=20
  internally use some additional variables such as length of the data =
compressed=20
  so far since that is needed for the length padding in the end. See the =
<A=20
  class=3Dmw-redirect title=3D"Merkle-Damg=C3=A5rd construction"=20
  =
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Merkle-Damg%C3%A5rd_construction">Me=
rkle-Damg=C3=A5rd=20
  construction</A> for details.</SPAN></LI>
  <LI id=3Dcite_note-13><SPAN class=3Dmw-cite-backlink><B><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCryptographic_hash_fu=
nction&amp;oldid=3D537036494#cite_ref-13">^</A></B></SPAN>=20
  <SPAN class=3Dreference-text>When omitted, rounds are full =
number.</SPAN></LI>
  <LI id=3Dcite_note-14><SPAN class=3Dmw-cite-backlink><B><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCryptographic_hash_fu=
nction&amp;oldid=3D537036494#cite_ref-14">^</A></B></SPAN>=20
  <SPAN class=3Dreference-text>Although the underlying algorithm <A=20
  class=3Dmw-redirect title=3DKeccak=20
  href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keccak">Keccak</A> has arbitrary =
hash=20
  lengths, the NIST specified 224, 256, 384 and 512 bits output as valid =
modes=20
  for SHA-3.</SPAN></LI></OL>
